postcontent:
I am the original owner on all items. I always buy new and they are gently used and well maintained for the next owner.  
RIA 1911 is brand new**, purchased Saturday 8.4.12.  I will use the setup until it is sold.   Included is a tactical solutions .22 conversion slide called the 2011.  See their website for details.  Finally, a new 5.11 tactical range duffel bag that I will use until items sell.  I may throw in a box of ammo free depending on what I have at the moment.

Rock Island Armory 1911-A1 Tactical .45 ACP 5 Inch Barrel Parkerized Finish 8

Round Rock Island Armory 1911 Tactical
Novak style fixed, front and rear sights. Dove tail front sight. Ambidextrous safety, beaver tail, skeletonized trigger, commander hammer and smooth wood grips.
Caliber: .45 ACP
Magazine Capacity: 8
Finish: Parkerized
Barrel Length: 5 (note, slide has gold lettering of RIA on left side of slide)

http://www.tacticalsol.com/tshome/2211-1911-22lr-conversion (note, TS barrel is not threaded as shown in reference picture).

http://www.511tactical.com/All-Products/Bags-Backpacks/Range-Gear/Range-Ready-Bag.html

Email for pictures.  Post will be updated on first request.

**Range report for Monday Aug 6, 2012.  The 45 setup shot fantastic.  I could not be more pleased after 50 rounds.  I have owned 1911's that cost more than double and I have to say I am impressed.  The real surprise is from the .22 slide conversion.  I shot 12 full magazines (10 round capacity) and had a slide lock 10/12 mag loads.  This is definitely an improvement over some of the other 1911's I have shot with the conversion unit.  But that is not what impressed me, the ability to nail the bulls 10-ring bullet after bullet after bullet.  The RIA 1911 is a fantastic platform for the .22 slide straight out of the box.  I only meant to warm up with the .22 to learn the new trigger on the RIA platform but kept reloading and smiling after each grouping in the 10-ring.  It was addicting.

This is definitely a great setup.  Learn the trigger and make grip/aim corrections using $0.04 a round then change the slide and let the 45's rip a hole in the bulls.  You get 525 rounds for $19 (Federal 36 gr) vs 50 rounds for $21 (or $10 if you load your own and get free brass).  Either way, you can't beat the trigger and flinch training from the conversion slide.  The solid steel setup mimics the native 45 slide setup so weight and holster draw is the same.
